		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_922610"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Dryfft</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Has anyone actually received a new job offer, and then a counter-offer from your current company, and had following success?<br />
<br />
Is it still considered best practice to keep tight-lipped about reasons for accepting an offer, or reasons for leaving when talking to your current company?</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Never had a good experience accepting or even entertaining counter offers from current companies.  In my experience it is one of times where you really see what your current employer is made out of when you give your notice.  I've had it go either way.<br />
<br />
I always try to be as tight lipped as possible when leaving a company.  The one time where I gave a reason for leaving I had it thrown in my face in the subsequent conversation.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
