	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_922645">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_922645">Whenever entertaining an offer, be careful of the special things a company may throw at you (whether your current employer or prospective) when they're desperate to get/keep you. A friend went to a new company last year because they were going to let her work from home much of the time. New management comes in a few months later and revokes that. She even had it in writing but I think they threw in some generic clause that allowed them to cancel it. She should have added her own clause that stated they would compensate her should the work from home privilege be cancelled. Don't let this happen to you!<br />
<br />
As for reasons why you'd leave, remain vague...needed a change of scenery...great opportunity....blah blah...<br />
<br />
...that is, unless you really want them to make a counter-offer. Then play up whatever it is you're after. If your new company is offering you a 10% increase in pay tell your current employer they offered you 15%. If they want to keep you that badly then let them pay you accordingly.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=123067" target="_blank">Merko - Gnome Mage</a>
			</div>
		<!-- / sig -->
		
		
		
	
	</td>
